>I've seen it pay off in Call of the Waifur and no other story
… are you only browsing stories with the /adhg/ tag? You're leaving out Smiling's worldbuilding – which is extensive enough that it warrants its own docs – and Mousguy's BHA docs. I agree with the sentiment that fantasy and sci-fi settings benefit from solid in-story worldbuilding, but it's tricky to carry out in the scale of a short story, or plot-focused chapters. I've been a cautious proponent of depthy worldbuilding myself, but a story's focus should be on its plot and characters. To their credit, most writers here don't try to expand their SOL urban romances into anything more than is necessary for plot progression and character development, which is as it should be.

Anonymous Sat 04 Dec 2021 08:15:23 No.43695934 Report

>>43694744
Yeah, I feel ya' there—you and I are more or less of one mind on that. Character and plot form the meaty heart that a story really hinges on. There's a reason you can get by without ever building your setting, after all. Setting is more of a... conversational ice breaker. In the beginning, new writers hinged their first stories on novelty, the first being species (this is why we have so many stories with punny, referential titles dated '17-'19), with setting following that until mid-'18, when more of us enjoyed talking about plot ideas & scenarios (doesn't occur to that extent anymore, sadly). Writers sort of stopped exploring novelty through species when favorites were cemented between Anons and writefags alike.

That all said, the best settings are either subject to characterization themselves (eg, the bowels of a spaceship succumbing to deep space), or very subtly reveal in passive minutia just how exotic they really are. Narrative, which marries plot progression and characterization, is more critical to what makes a story than setting itself, and even that follows the creation of plot at times.
